title: For Sale:  Mosin Nagant 91/30 M.O. 1939/50 Double Date marked stamped Tula Arsenal Matching Serial Numbers
location: North Branch, Minneapolis / St. Paul, Minnesota
postcontent:
1939/51 Mosin Nagant M.O. Marked Stamped Double Date Tula Arsenal Matching Serial Numbers 

Has all matching STAMPED serial numbers on Bolt, Floor Plate, and Receiver This is a century import has all the normal accessories. Bayonet that fits the barrel, Oilier/Cleaner can, cleaning tools, 2 ammo pouches, head space gauge, and Sling.

The 1939 year and older production do have a much better finish compared to the 1940-1944. Also there are far fewer 1939 and older most of the rifles you find were made during the height of WWII. This is a pre war built rifle

This has the Tula star as the Arsenal that it was built at according to some this arsenal built more accurate rifle. 

M.O. Marking... Double Date From the research I have done this means it was built in 1939 and then issued to the Ministry of Defense in 1950 . Possibly guarded a government installation at that time. title: For Sale:  10 Boxes Russian 7.62x38R Nagant Ammo - Brass Case, Steel Core
postcontent:
I found a near full spam can of this Russian made 7.62x38 ammo recently while cleaning my ammo vault. I've owned at least a half dozen Nagant Revolvers over the years and fired them extensively. To me they were always one of the finest surplus handguns ever brought to the states. That said I've always found that the real Russian surplus ammo was the very best shooting ammo. It's clean, dependable and designed specifically for the Nagant. Plus it features a heavier 108 grain bullet with a steel core while the commercially loaded stuff has a lead core 98 grain bullet. Then to me at least the Russian ammo seemed to be loaded noticeably hotter than what you can get from PPU or Fiocchi. I suppose it's a liability issue? The last piece is that the Russian ammo always shot more accurately. The only negative at all is that this ammo does use a corrosive primer so cleaning your gun is a must after using. Listing is for (10) 14 boxes or 140 rounds total. Head stamp is 38, 77 meaning it was produced at the Russian State Factory at Yuryusan, Russia in 1977. However it looks like it was made yesterday.

Asking price is $80. FTT with pickup in the Brandon area. You must be at least 21 to purchase.

title: For Sale:  SAKO Finnbear L61R 30-06 (Pre-Garcia)
location: Newport, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
What's Pre-Garcia?  It means a better stock finish.  Some of the Garcia's I've owned become sticky and lost their luster.  As you can see this one shines like new.  This particular rifle was imported by Firearms International (FI) in 1969. As well Garcia's don't show the quality in action and barrel polishing and so will not have the mirror finish.  In lower left photo you can see the partial  reflection of the scope lens cap in the shine on the barrel.  You'll notice the early models show a more immediate contour as the barrel leaves the action.  Late models are quite different.  Buying a Pre-Garcia ensures you a better value in the future.  You simply won't go wrong. Front sight hoods are missing from MANY SAKO's.  Not mine! Factory Hoods cost $100 or more if you can even find one.  SAKO Collectors demand original parts.  I fired less than 300 rounds through this rifle and decided it was a real keeper.  It this rifle has been a "Safe Queen" as I had many other rifles to shoot.  Very accurate, everything I fired shot well under an inch.  Some were half inch.  I put this away thinking I'd hunt with it some day.  43 years later... it's still there.  I hate to part with it, but I have an overabundance of 30-06 rifles, and just purchased a SAKO 7mm Mag.

The Weaver T-16 and Sako Hi Rings ARE NOT INCLUDED and are NOT FOR SALE

I'm asking a fair price for this beauty, and I'm sure you will agree it's one of the best other than new you've seen.  I know there are a number to choose from.  But who else dares to show their rifle in close up photos like these.  Beware of rifles with lines in the finish.  These have been subjected to temperature extremes which cracked the finish.  There is NO WAY to restore the original appearance.  It won't affect the accuracy, only the value of the rifle.

Payment must come ONLY in the form of a US Postal Money Order".  Shipping and insurance is $32 fixed for CONUS. Call David at REDACTED with any questions or concerns.  Additional photos available upon request.  Reasonable offers will be considered.
